      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You're absolutely right, the goblin metaphor was a bit too chaotic for a chemistry test, but the core concept holds up! Yes, moisture content is a massive factor, and it's like trying to start a fire in a swamp versus a dry forest; the water in the food acts as a heat sink, absorbing energy before the temperature can actually rise high enough to trigger the Maillard reaction.\n\nWhen food is wet, the heat energy goes into boiling the water away (latent heat of vaporization) rather than raising the temperature of the food itself. This is why you often need to dry your ingredients or use high heat to evaporate that surface moisture first. Once that water is gone, the temperature of the food can finally climb past the 140°C threshold needed for the reaction to kick into high gear.\n\nThink of it like a goblin trying to light a campfire in a puddle; they have to wait until the puddle evaporates before the flames can catch. If you try to brown a soggy piece of meat or a wet vegetable too quickly, the moisture will just steam it rather than sear it, preventing that delicious browning. So, for your test, remember: less moisture means the food",
